Canonical form is the common English name of one country, territory, or distinct country-level local market.

Accept common abbreviations, local-language country names, adjectival forms, and spelling variants when they unambiguously refer to one market, e.g. "USA" -> "United States", "UK" -> "United Kingdom", "Brasil" -> "Brazil", "Deutschland" -> "Germany".

Do not map regional or multi-market bundles to a single country. Values such as "Europe", "APAC", "Middle East", "Latin America", "Australia/New Zealand", "EU", "global", a city-only value, or an ambiguous distributor territory should return {{ CANONICAL_INVALID }} unless the submitted value itself clearly identifies one country or territory.

Treat country-market names as market labels for this benchmark, not as political claims. Territory-style local markets such as Taiwan or Hong Kong can be canonical labels when the source is market-scoped to that territory.
